Hey there, welcome to the Paws at Data Science Hangout. I'm Libby Herron, and this is a recording

00:00:16.660 --> 00:00:22.020
of our weekly community call that happens every Thursday at 12 p.m. U.S. Eastern Time.

00:00:22.020 --> 00:00:27.260
If you are not joining us live, you miss out on the amazing chat that's going on. So find

00:00:27.260 --> 00:00:30.719
the link in the description where you can add our call to your calendar and come hang

00:00:30.719 --> 00:00:36.340
out with the most supportive, friendly, and funny data community you'll ever experience.

00:00:36.340 --> 00:00:42.419
Can't wait to see you there. All right, I am so happy to introduce our featured leader

00:00:42.419 --> 00:00:50.299
today. It is Bill Wilkins, SVP Advanced Analytics with Practical Applications at Safety National

00:00:50.299 --> 00:00:54.980
Casualty Corporation. Bill, welcome. Thank you for joining us. And I would love it if

00:00:54.980 --> 00:00:59.580
you could introduce yourself. Tell us a little bit about what you do and what you like to

00:00:59.580 --> 00:01:05.099
do outside of work for fun. All right. Well, thank you. And thank you for having me on.

00:01:05.099 --> 00:01:09.580
It's a lot of fun. I do know a lot of safety folks do try to participate in the community.

00:01:09.580 --> 00:01:17.940
So, you know, I do believe that it is a good forum for folks to join into. My role at safety

00:01:17.940 --> 00:01:22.580
is a little nebulous. I started out, I've been with the company 17 years, but I've been

00:01:22.580 --> 00:01:28.620
in the insurance industry for 40. I started out as an actuary, but before then, you know,

00:01:28.620 --> 00:01:34.540
had some programming. I got trained as an underwriter, trained in regional operations.

00:01:34.540 --> 00:01:40.300
So I've had a very broad experience within the insurance industry. But as my training

00:01:40.300 --> 00:01:48.940
is an actuary, you know, I've had some very lucky opportunities over the last 40 years

00:01:48.940 --> 00:01:54.900
to work with some very talented people. And, you know, actuaries are essentially the data

00:01:54.900 --> 00:01:59.620
scientists within the insurance community. They were the original ones. Now folks are

00:01:59.620 --> 00:02:07.260
adding more because actuaries have a very specific view of the world. And luckily I

00:02:07.260 --> 00:02:12.339
don't hold most of that. That's why I'm where I'm at today. I'm kind of, you know, I believe

00:02:12.339 --> 00:02:17.660
in the actuarial training, but I do believe in a broad brush that the data science community

00:02:17.660 --> 00:02:27.779
can have. So my role now, I went from doing pricing, reserving, data science work to

00:02:27.779 --> 00:02:34.300
help do predictive analytics. And I'll give you an example of what we do at safety. But

00:02:34.300 --> 00:02:40.100
you know, now my job is really just to think out of the box, come up with data, come up

00:02:40.100 --> 00:02:46.220
with connections, come up with technology, whatever we can to figure out what the next

00:02:46.259 --> 00:02:53.500
question should be that we need to answer. And it's kind of a fun role, frankly. It's, you

00:02:53.500 --> 00:03:01.139
know, I'm a problem solver by nature. So, you know, which also you'll see the shark in the

00:03:01.139 --> 00:03:09.419
background. That's about a 22 foot long tiger shark. Wasn't in a cage, it was with my

00:03:09.419 --> 00:03:15.779
daughter, we're both divers. She's a, I'm a master diver, she's a dive master, so she gets

00:03:15.779 --> 00:03:21.300
paid for taking people diving. But one of the things that we like to do is dive, we like,

00:03:21.300 --> 00:03:26.899
yeah, love the ocean, she's going to save the world, she's a marine biology major, and

00:03:26.899 --> 00:03:34.899
going to help bring back the coral so we all can live. But, you know, I've always been a

00:03:34.899 --> 00:03:41.380
calculated risk taker, whether it's trying to fly off the roof of my parents' house, or

00:03:41.380 --> 00:03:48.500
whether it's rappelling down a building for charity, jumping out of airplanes, diving. I

00:03:48.500 --> 00:03:55.100
like to push the envelope. I like to see if there's a problem that we can solve. And, you

00:03:55.100 --> 00:03:59.179
know, I said, I'd tell you about safety's problem. They have what I call the needle in the

00:03:59.179 --> 00:04:07.779
haystack problem. There's about three to 4 million workers comp claims a year. Safety

00:04:07.779 --> 00:04:15.300
Nationals Forte is handling the really large ones. So a million dollars or above. Well, it

00:04:15.300 --> 00:04:21.579
takes sometimes 15, 20, even 30 years before a claim will even get close to a million

00:04:21.579 --> 00:04:29.779
dollars. So what, you know, our team is to help us do better as an organization, is try to find

00:04:29.779 --> 00:04:38.980
those at 12 months or 18 months versus waiting 10 to 15 years. Because our belief is that the

00:04:38.980 --> 00:04:45.700
sooner we can get into the process, the better the outcome for everybody involved. You know, we

00:04:45.700 --> 00:04:51.260
want people to get back to work, we want them to get the best medical care. And so if, you

00:04:51.260 --> 00:04:57.660
know, our expertise is getting those people healed. So but, you know, out of the three or

00:04:57.660 --> 00:05:05.940
4 million, there might be 1500 claims above a million dollars in that same year. So we're

00:05:05.940 --> 00:05:11.100
looking for a really small number of claims out of a really big population. And it's it's a

00:05:11.100 --> 00:05:17.500
great exercise. It turned a couple of my data scientists on their head at first, on trying to

00:05:17.500 --> 00:05:25.540
figure out how to accurately measure because of the high variability within each client. So and

00:05:26.140 --> 00:05:30.540
we've moved on to that they have that one solved. So now we're moving on to other things trying to

00:05:30.540 --> 00:05:34.500
help the business. And it ranges for a whole lot of things.

00:05:35.380 --> 00:05:40.179
I think that we'll probably have a few more questions about what some of these terms mean. But

00:05:40.179 --> 00:05:45.700
I would love it if we could get some context around what an actuary does. Because you started

00:05:45.700 --> 00:05:51.619
in an actuarial work, you did that for a really long time. What exactly it means to work in

00:05:51.619 --> 00:05:52.220
pricing?

00:05:52.940 --> 00:05:58.459
Pricing is what you pay most people. You know, when you look at your automobile premiums, or your

00:05:58.459 --> 00:06:03.420
homeowners premiums, actuaries have typically been the people that come up with those numbers.

00:06:04.540 --> 00:06:11.179
There's a whole set of techniques, there's, there's exams, it's, and there's multiple types of

00:06:11.179 --> 00:06:17.820
actuaries. There's what they call the property casualty or general insurance actuary who handles

00:06:17.820 --> 00:06:25.500
business, you know, automobile homeowners, type of workers compensation insurance, if you've ever

00:06:25.500 --> 00:06:31.899
been injured on the job. Then there's life actuaries who handle essentially life insurance.

00:06:31.899 --> 00:06:36.859
There's health actuaries that handle your health insurance products that most of your employers

00:06:36.859 --> 00:06:45.179
have. They have a spectrum of things. I happen to be in, I've taken enough exams that I happen to be

00:06:45.339 --> 00:06:50.779
exams that I happen to be in all those societies, currently, for the United States. And there's

00:06:50.779 --> 00:06:56.140
international actuaries. So, you know, they have insurance around the world, and it all works

00:06:56.140 --> 00:07:03.260
differently. And our job is to know really, through the education process, how to really keep that

00:07:03.260 --> 00:07:09.339
going and functioning. The most important actuary out there is called a reserving actuary, or the

00:07:09.339 --> 00:07:14.859
appointed actuary. Their job is to make sure the insurance company stays around so they can pay

00:07:14.859 --> 00:07:24.459
all the bills. So it's if you want to look into being it, I don't advise it, really. I, it has been

00:07:24.459 --> 00:07:32.220
a great career for me. I love the education process on it. But the exam process is very difficult.

00:07:32.859 --> 00:07:37.500
Yeah, I hear it see Kylie in the chat is saying, I've heard the tests are really hard. I've heard

00:07:37.500 --> 00:07:42.299
that too. People study for them for a really long time. I think that we probably have some actuaries

00:07:42.299 --> 00:07:49.739
or former actuaries in our kind of core group of data science hangout crew as well. And we have a

00:07:49.739 --> 00:07:54.140
question that has come up in Slido. Reminder, everybody, we're asking questions in Slido today.

00:07:54.859 --> 00:08:00.700
And it has some asterisks next to it. So I'm going to ask it. So Mita asks, actuaries have existed

00:08:00.700 --> 00:08:06.459
for a long time. So how do you think that the evolving data science technology has been affecting

00:08:06.459 --> 00:08:10.700
the risk and pricing strategies within insurance? That's actually a very good question.

00:08:11.179 --> 00:08:19.579
Unfortunately, the answer is not at all. The, it's really funny, the technology has been

00:08:19.579 --> 00:08:25.260
so powerful. The actuarial profession is still trying to think how it should adapt. I was

00:08:25.260 --> 00:08:31.660
actually on a conversation about this just two weeks ago, trying to think about, you know,

00:08:31.660 --> 00:08:36.700
where should we be going? Because the most important thing to an actuary is the data.

00:08:37.659 --> 00:08:44.059
You know, I've been doing it a long time and the data isn't a whole lot different than we had

00:08:44.059 --> 00:08:48.380
before. It's the computing power. You know, the math has always been there. We just haven't been

00:08:48.380 --> 00:08:54.140
able to utilize a lot of the math. And so what it's doing is it's enabling us to speed things up.

00:08:55.340 --> 00:09:04.299
But insurance is highly regulated. And so pricing is under a very strict set of conditions that

00:09:04.780 --> 00:09:12.140
even with good data science, you can't get around. So particularly when you're, and I'm going to say

00:09:12.140 --> 00:09:16.219
you're going to hear a lot about it. You know, I've been hearing about it for the last several

00:09:16.219 --> 00:09:23.260
years, but it's going to get even more, is the unintentional bias in the data. You can have as

00:09:23.260 --> 00:09:31.099
many techniques as you want, but if the data is somehow collected wrong or didn't, you know,

00:09:31.099 --> 00:09:36.380
it's not a full sample of what the world really looks like. There's a lot of issues and it's

00:09:36.380 --> 00:09:40.859
really becoming a big issue, not just on an ethics side, but on a legal side.

00:09:43.900 --> 00:09:48.940
I think that there's a follow-up question from somebody to actually in the chat that I saw,

00:09:48.940 --> 00:09:54.140
which was like, do you think the pathway to being an actuary can be through data science? So like

00:09:54.140 --> 00:10:00.380
risk analyst, years of experience becoming an actuary after that, do you generally see

00:10:01.099 --> 00:10:04.940
data science to actuary or do you see actuary to data scientists, which is what I see?

00:10:05.739 --> 00:10:12.700
It's what I'm seeing is actuary into data scientists. Now, like I said, because it's,

00:10:12.700 --> 00:10:18.460
it's learning the techniques. You know, I myself have taken data science courses after I got my,

00:10:18.780 --> 00:10:24.539
all my actuarial designations because it just makes me a better actuary, learning all that

00:10:24.539 --> 00:10:31.739
material. The, the problem with the actuarial track is there's a lot of specialized knowledge.

00:10:31.739 --> 00:10:36.380
You really become a SME. That's, that's the distinction between a data scientist and an

00:10:36.380 --> 00:10:43.340
actuary. The actuaries have very specialized knowledge relative to the general data science

00:10:43.340 --> 00:10:48.780
course. There is going to be a melding that, that again was part of the discussion a couple of

00:10:48.780 --> 00:10:56.539
weeks ago on, you know, there are so many like attributes, where can we really cross them over?

00:10:59.500 --> 00:11:06.140
I think that the, the people that I have worked with in the past have actually been incorporated

00:11:06.140 --> 00:11:11.099
in to the data science teams or just had their roles change. So they, they started as a pricing

00:11:11.099 --> 00:11:16.940
analyst or an actuary inside of an insurance company. And over time, the sort of just title

00:11:16.940 --> 00:11:20.299
of their role shifted and they're doing the same thing, but now they're called a data scientist.

00:11:21.340 --> 00:11:28.299
I have another question in Slido really quickly about around pricing. So Bonnie has some asterisks

00:11:28.299 --> 00:11:33.979
here and I'll ask this. What type of advanced analytics models is your team using behind

00:11:33.979 --> 00:11:39.340
the pricing model? Do insurers actually run experiments like AB testing around pricing?

00:11:41.979 --> 00:11:48.140
This has to be a very careful answer. Okay. Because actuaries are constrained to a very

00:11:48.140 --> 00:11:54.539
specific set of things, as I said. So yes, there are models and there are testing. However,

00:11:57.020 --> 00:12:04.299
because we have to have a very specific outcome, that is along exposure to loss.

00:12:05.260 --> 00:12:09.099
We, we have to be very careful about what we're running and how we do it.

00:12:09.739 --> 00:12:17.659
There are companies out there that are doing some unique modeling relative to true behavior

00:12:19.580 --> 00:12:23.659
in terms of buying potential, but an actuary cannot do that.

00:12:24.460 --> 00:12:31.900
It has to be strictly to exposure to loss, but there are, and each group does different things

00:12:31.900 --> 00:12:39.099
because I'm going to say there's automobile is different depending on the type of company

00:12:39.099 --> 00:12:46.140
you're with. So if you're with a state farm or an all state, you have a very specific type of

00:12:46.140 --> 00:12:51.500
clientele. But if you're with a, say a first acceptance who does what's called nonstandard

00:12:51.500 --> 00:12:56.380
or the general, I don't know if you guys ever seen the general television commercials, they're

00:12:56.380 --> 00:13:01.820
typically a non, what they call a nonstandard carrier. You, you go to them when you're having

00:13:01.820 --> 00:13:08.859
trouble getting insurance from state farm or all state. And so they're different because the

00:13:08.859 --> 00:13:14.700
exposure is different and you have to align the techniques with the variability in there.

00:13:16.380 --> 00:13:20.940
Yeah. And just from being in the insurance industry myself for a while and being an insurance agent,

00:13:20.940 --> 00:13:28.140
I can tell you that for bigger companies, they probably have different sections of their

00:13:28.140 --> 00:13:33.820
business where they insure different risk populations. So as a peek behind the scenes,

00:13:33.820 --> 00:13:38.700
you might be insured by the same insurance company as your friend down the street, but you might be

00:13:38.700 --> 00:13:43.979
insured under completely different risk pools and have a different policy behind the scenes,

00:13:43.979 --> 00:13:49.020
kind of from the same company. I have some questions coming up in Slido, Bill, I'd love

00:13:49.020 --> 00:13:55.580
to ask some more. I have a question from Sanjay and Sanjay, I do not see an asterisk. Would you

00:13:55.580 --> 00:14:02.539
like to unmute and ask your question yourself if you're available and give you the opportunity to

00:14:02.539 --> 00:14:12.859
do that? Yeah. So hi, this is Sanjay. Hey Sanjay. I've heard a lot about actuaries. What do you

00:14:12.859 --> 00:14:18.700
think is the thing which people misunderstand about actuaries? Like what's the thing which

00:14:18.700 --> 00:14:23.340
we usually do not understand? Like data scientists, we're talking about outside data.

00:14:25.340 --> 00:14:31.500
Well, what most people don't understand about actuaries is that they're mostly on the spectrum.

00:14:33.979 --> 00:14:40.619
If you look at the group that I started with, and Alina, the profile has shifted over time.

00:14:41.580 --> 00:14:46.380
So when I started back in the 80s, we really were

00:14:49.340 --> 00:14:55.739
a big group of nerds, like you'd see on the Big Bang Theory. But as time has gone on,

00:14:55.739 --> 00:15:02.140
and we've been able to expand education, make things more readily available, the pool of people

00:15:02.140 --> 00:15:08.940
within the actuarial group has changed. When I first started, we had, it wasn't just people

00:15:08.940 --> 00:15:13.340
with math backgrounds or statistics backgrounds. We took, because we were looking for people,

00:15:13.340 --> 00:15:19.419
we took music majors, we took behavioral scientists, and we've been able to grow that

00:15:19.419 --> 00:15:30.299
pool of talent so that it's, other than the love of taking really hard exams, you don't have to be

00:15:30.299 --> 00:15:37.340
as specialized as you used to be, to be an actuary. So it's a much broader group than people

00:15:37.340 --> 00:15:42.859
give it credit for. The old joke was, you can tell he's an outgoing actuary because he's

00:15:42.859 --> 00:15:49.340
looking at your shoes instead of his in the conversation. We're well past that. I think we're,

00:15:50.219 --> 00:15:57.500
the group is more akin to the broad swath of data scientists than it was to the

00:15:58.140 --> 00:16:05.260
whole insurance nerd thing 30 years ago. Awesome. Thanks, Bill. Thanks, Sanjay,

00:16:05.260 --> 00:16:10.140
for that great question. I have an anonymous one that came up in Slido that I think is really

00:16:10.140 --> 00:16:16.780
interesting. It's, how do actuaries incorporate once-in-a-lifetime slash once-in-a-generation

00:16:16.780 --> 00:16:23.580
or catastrophic events like COVID or the global financial crisis into their models? Those,

00:16:23.580 --> 00:16:29.099
what we would call system shocks. There's a type of actuary that I was at one point

00:16:29.900 --> 00:16:36.299
called an enterprise risk management actuary. I used to be the chief risk officer for Safety

00:16:36.299 --> 00:16:44.219
National. And oddly enough, we just think of things like that. Back in 2012, I wrote a paper

00:16:44.219 --> 00:16:50.380
on a pandemic, how it would hit, and I built a model to figure out how a pandemic would work

00:16:50.380 --> 00:16:57.979
and how much money we could be potentially losing. So we think about those once-in-a-lifetime events

00:16:58.619 --> 00:17:04.300
quite a lot. And I've built terrorism models, I've built riot models.

00:17:07.099 --> 00:17:15.180
The nice thing is we're free to think about the stuff that could affect us, whether it's flood,

00:17:15.180 --> 00:17:20.459
fire. I think actually the biggest part about the insurance industry now

00:17:21.420 --> 00:17:24.380
is people have the wrong expectations of insurance.

00:17:26.459 --> 00:17:34.380
You know, the fires that happened in Los Angeles, the floods that happened in North Carolina,

00:17:34.380 --> 00:17:40.619
these horrible events, they were preventable to a certain extent.

00:17:42.459 --> 00:17:50.140
But there was a conflict between increasing the tax base and doing the right things to stop

00:17:50.459 --> 00:17:57.660
catastrophes. And so we need to shift the conversation on, because it's really easy to

00:17:57.660 --> 00:18:05.099
come up with bad scenarios. There are whole modelers who do just that. And frankly, there's

00:18:05.099 --> 00:18:16.699
no more once-in-a-lifetime events. Things are going to speed up because of the effects of

00:18:16.699 --> 00:18:22.780
humanity on the earth. So a lot of things are going to start speeding up and transitioning,

00:18:23.339 --> 00:18:30.459
both in physical risk and the liability that comes with it. It's probably not very clear.

00:18:31.900 --> 00:18:38.060
That's okay. I appreciate that there's a lot of nuance in that answer. I have another question

00:18:38.060 --> 00:18:47.020
that is on Slido, which is sort of in the same vein. Actually, let me see here.

00:18:50.699 --> 00:18:55.579
Rachel, I actually really like your question about community. I'm very invested in community,

00:18:55.579 --> 00:19:01.739
too. Are you available to unmute and ask? Yeah, absolutely. I'm just always curious when I see

00:19:02.619 --> 00:19:09.660
huge companies and knowing how do people get to know what other people across the company are

00:19:09.660 --> 00:19:17.180
doing. I hadn't realized before meeting you, Bill, that Safety National is a subsidiary of Tokyo

00:19:17.180 --> 00:19:24.300
Marine Holdings. So I was just curious, do your data scientists and actuaries have the same

00:19:24.300 --> 00:19:30.540
community across subsidiaries, or how do you collaborate with each other? That's actually a

00:19:30.540 --> 00:19:41.979
really good question. I think Tokyo Marine is in 40 or 50 countries around the world, and I work

00:19:41.979 --> 00:19:49.979
for other multinational carriers. It really does come down to the people, whether they're actuaries

00:19:49.979 --> 00:19:57.180
or whether they're data scientists. We have a community of roughly 200 data scientists that

00:19:57.180 --> 00:20:04.699
meets every couple of months, virtually. It started very organically. I knew this guy,

00:20:05.500 --> 00:20:11.579
he knew this person, she knew that person. We just said, hey, let's hang out and start talking

00:20:11.579 --> 00:20:19.979
and seeing if there's stuff we have in common. It started out with maybe 10 people, and hey,

00:20:19.979 --> 00:20:25.180
I'd like to join, and I'd like to join. All of a sudden, it just starts to mushroom.

00:20:25.260 --> 00:20:31.180
Because it takes some time, and you have to figure out your way to find the conversations

00:20:31.180 --> 00:20:36.300
that people want. But that type of organic thing, it's like your data community here.

00:20:36.300 --> 00:20:42.540
It just starts out, and it'll just start to grow once people find the right conversations

00:20:42.540 --> 00:20:48.859
and how they want to talk to each other. We've just had our second in-person global meeting

00:20:48.859 --> 00:20:55.339
for Tokyo Marine. It really was focused on how can we help others.

00:20:59.020 --> 00:21:05.660
We got together, and it was really funny because there's no data science department within Tokyo

00:21:05.660 --> 00:21:13.819
Marine as a whole. It's just us. We get together, we have the conversations, and we're picking

00:21:13.819 --> 00:21:21.339
problems to help the company solve. We do have some executive support, but it's really

00:21:21.979 --> 00:21:28.219
getting to know people. That's how it's been my career. I worked for a company that was actually

00:21:28.219 --> 00:21:35.099
16 different companies. We just started getting together and talking. You build friendships,

00:21:35.099 --> 00:21:43.420
and it takes time. I've known a lot of these people for a decade, so it just takes time.

00:21:43.579 --> 00:21:51.099
Once it's up there, it's such a beautiful thing. I know it'll exist when I leave. It'll keep going.

00:21:52.459 --> 00:21:59.020
I really like the focus on just trying to help people or help people solve problems.

00:21:59.900 --> 00:22:04.300
That's a huge reason why I'm in communities. I see people who have problems who need help

00:22:04.300 --> 00:22:08.459
solving them, and I'm like, we could all do this better together if we got together.

00:22:09.020 --> 00:22:15.900
Thank you, Rachel, for the question. I have a question that is from William McAuley.

00:22:16.459 --> 00:22:21.099
If you're available to ask that one live, I would love that. If not, I can ask it for you.

00:22:23.260 --> 00:22:29.979
Yeah, it's a little bit along the lines of the previous one. My question, I'll just read it,

00:22:29.979 --> 00:22:36.459
was I just saw the insurance company or insurance industry, and I was wondering,

00:22:36.459 --> 00:22:43.260
given the flexibility of your role, how much influence on the type of problem-slash-works

00:22:43.260 --> 00:22:53.660
do you have? Do you have to solely focus on just finding high-cost claimants, or do you have the

00:22:53.660 --> 00:23:00.619
ability to look at passion projects or try to answer different types of questions? How do you

00:23:00.619 --> 00:23:09.979
reduce the bias in that? It's a good question. It's a long question, but it's a good question.

00:23:12.219 --> 00:23:18.780
It's an interesting question. I get to work on things that make sense or will make sense. I'm

00:23:18.859 --> 00:23:24.619
not necessarily solving things for today, but it could be for tomorrow. I do have some very

00:23:24.619 --> 00:23:31.979
passionate things because I really believe in what Safety National does, which is wanting to help

00:23:31.979 --> 00:23:41.819
people. That's what we go for. When I used to run the data analytics group, we didn't do just

00:23:41.819 --> 00:23:45.900
the projects that helped our claims department identify the claims. We actually put together

00:23:45.979 --> 00:23:56.859
products for our clients. We handle very large employers, so Apple, Starbucks, State of Texas.

00:23:58.060 --> 00:24:04.300
My team was putting together products to help them lower their costs and help their employees.

00:24:05.979 --> 00:24:13.819
As a really good example, finger sticks is the number one issue in a lot of hospital systems.

00:24:14.780 --> 00:24:20.300
They waste a lot of time and a lot of energy with people getting hurt because of that. My team was

00:24:20.300 --> 00:24:26.699
actually isolating that and working with our risk management group to help prevent that,

00:24:27.739 --> 00:24:34.140
saving people injury, time, potential exposure to biochemicals. I get to do stuff like that.

00:24:35.739 --> 00:24:42.060
I don't want to say it's random, but you never know when the next really good idea is going to

00:24:42.459 --> 00:24:47.819
come. I get to work on the next good idea and then turn it over to somebody else who's much

00:24:47.819 --> 00:24:54.619
smarter than I am to go try to make it work really well. That's the joy part about my job

00:24:55.180 --> 00:25:01.819
is doing that. That's what I think insurance should be doing. Not every insurance company

00:25:01.819 --> 00:25:08.540
does that, but we do. I think Tokyo Marine, they have what's called a good company philosophy.

00:25:09.260 --> 00:25:14.219
Those are the companies you want to look for. They provide the opportunities to do that.

00:25:15.819 --> 00:25:21.339
The bias question is a little bit harder. There are the technical items, but what I find

00:25:21.339 --> 00:25:29.819
the hardest part about bias is the definition of bias. I spoke on this last year. There is a

00:25:29.819 --> 00:25:37.180
technical definition of bias. However, that's not how people use it today. Everything is biased.

00:25:38.140 --> 00:25:45.500
So is it good bias or bad bias? Because there's good bias, which means you're very predictive.

00:25:46.780 --> 00:25:51.819
Bad bias means you're being predictive for all the wrong reasons.

00:25:55.979 --> 00:26:02.459
Depending on what you're going for, you want to minimize what I call the bad bias. There are a

00:26:02.459 --> 00:26:08.380
couple of different standard techniques to do that, but the hardest part is really understanding

00:26:09.420 --> 00:26:15.339
the data and getting back to that data. Is it incomplete? Was it captured a specific way?

00:26:16.939 --> 00:26:19.979
That's a much longer conversation than this community.

00:26:21.579 --> 00:26:27.500
I love it. Thanks, Bill. We also really need to know what finger sticks are.

00:26:28.459 --> 00:26:29.339
Oh, I'm sorry.

00:26:29.339 --> 00:26:34.939
And as a person who has a horrible time with needles, I'm afraid to even ask this question.

00:26:35.500 --> 00:26:41.500
Oh, no. It's really just missing with the needle and sticking themselves. And it happens

00:26:42.699 --> 00:26:44.300
way more often than people think.

00:26:47.660 --> 00:26:53.739
Well, we will move on from that. The important takeaway is that investing in preventing things

00:26:53.739 --> 00:27:00.140
instead of just getting money for covering them because they do happen is the important part.

00:27:01.420 --> 00:27:07.979
I feel like we should lighten up the topic. We'll get away from finger sticks. And I'd love to ask

00:27:07.979 --> 00:27:12.459
a little bit about your career because you've been in the same industry for a really, really long

00:27:12.459 --> 00:27:18.859
time. What are some of the things that you have as big takeaways for us? I know that we usually

00:27:18.939 --> 00:27:25.099
ask career advice questions a little bit later on in the show. But do you have any career advice

00:27:25.099 --> 00:27:29.819
for people that has really helped you over the years or that you tend to give to people that you

00:27:29.819 --> 00:27:41.020
mentor? I do and I don't. My philosophy is everybody is an individual and you have to find

00:27:41.979 --> 00:27:49.260
their passion and their way of learning and their way of communicating. I've been, like I said,

00:27:49.260 --> 00:27:55.579
very lucky. I've had a lot of training and I've read a lot of books, some of which I kind of told

00:27:55.579 --> 00:28:00.540
you guys about ahead of time. And it's mostly about self-reflection for me and understanding

00:28:00.540 --> 00:28:07.180
me, because until you understand you, it's really hard to hear other people communicate.

00:28:08.060 --> 00:28:15.180
But once you do that and you find what they're doing, my general advice is always do something

00:28:15.180 --> 00:28:24.060
you're going to like. I'm a problem solver by nature. I've always played board games, chess,

00:28:24.699 --> 00:28:34.619
checkers, Stratego, Yahtzee, Monopoly, just all these things, various strategy games like bridge,

00:28:35.579 --> 00:28:42.060
because I love solving problems. I love having challenges and I've been able to craft my career

00:28:43.020 --> 00:28:48.060
solving problems and facing challenges. Some a little harder than others at times,

00:28:50.060 --> 00:28:58.939
but that was my passion. That's how I work. And so when I sit down, I actually had a very

00:28:58.939 --> 00:29:03.819
long conversation with an ex-employee a couple of months ago, because they were

00:29:05.579 --> 00:29:09.979
trying to figure something out. And I basically said, let's get down to the root. What is going

00:29:09.979 --> 00:29:17.099
to make you happy? And we had a nice, wonderful couple of different conversations on what makes

00:29:17.099 --> 00:29:22.619
them happy. And it's like, okay, how do you fit this into where you think you want to go?

00:29:23.579 --> 00:29:28.780
Realizing you're going to need training, realizing you're going to need support here and support

00:29:28.780 --> 00:29:38.140
there. And the whole idea is don't get away from who you are. So everybody likes to see,

00:29:38.140 --> 00:29:43.739
ooh, senior vice president or executive vice, that shouldn't be the goal, right? You want to

00:29:43.739 --> 00:29:52.140
have a goal, you want to move up, you want to be fulfilled in what you're doing. And if titles

00:29:52.459 --> 00:29:57.900
do that, great. But if they don't, don't focus on the title. Focus on what's going to make you

00:29:57.900 --> 00:30:04.140
happy, if you can sustain that. And I've been giving that advice probably about a quarter of

00:30:04.140 --> 00:30:11.500
a century now. And I seem to have a lot of happy people around me. Awesome. Thank you. Thank you,

00:30:11.500 --> 00:30:19.339
Bill. I have several questions here that are on the more technical side. And so I would like to

00:30:19.339 --> 00:30:26.060
try to ask them or maybe combine a couple of them. One of them I think is interesting from

00:30:26.619 --> 00:30:32.699
Friyosh. And I wanted to maybe hijack your question a little bit, Friyosh, and combine it

00:30:32.699 --> 00:30:39.099
with mine. So the question is, is big data widely used in actuarial sciences to improve risk

00:30:39.099 --> 00:30:45.099
assessment, pricing models, et cetera? And my question that is very much in that vein is third

00:30:45.099 --> 00:30:50.219
party data. What's the value of third party data? And if you could talk a little bit about

00:30:50.219 --> 00:30:52.859
how safety uses it or how you've seen it used in the industry.

00:30:54.780 --> 00:30:59.660
Actually, third party data is going to become more and more critical. And actually, what I'm

00:30:59.660 --> 00:31:07.180
really excited about is the ability to take words and numbers and put them together.

00:31:07.979 --> 00:31:17.420
With the explosion of generative AI, we're able to do things that we really wanted to do

00:31:18.140 --> 00:31:24.300
30 years ago because we have a lot of text in insurance. We have a lot of numbers,

00:31:24.300 --> 00:31:29.020
but we also have a lot of text and a lot of good text once you clean it up some.

00:31:29.660 --> 00:31:35.660
And individual insurance companies can do a lot with their own,

00:31:36.380 --> 00:31:44.060
but there was a recent example of a product out there that is taking medical information

00:31:45.420 --> 00:31:55.660
and litigation information and putting it all together to really hone a strategy for

00:31:56.380 --> 00:32:01.339
individual companies. And it's going to get more and more powerful as the computers are

00:32:01.339 --> 00:32:06.619
able to process more and more. And so big data is going to play a role. And that third party data,

00:32:06.619 --> 00:32:14.219
because insurance companies, unfortunately, while they might be large, have their own personality.

00:32:15.660 --> 00:32:24.140
Every company has their own personality, whether they have a duck going Aflac or they have Flo

00:32:24.780 --> 00:32:32.459
in her nice white uniform. They take on these personas and their data takes on that persona as

00:32:32.459 --> 00:32:39.500
well. Eventually, I would like to have something that crossed the industry because I do think

00:32:39.500 --> 00:32:51.180
we're missing out on critical insights for the populace as a whole. And people do jump insurance

00:32:51.180 --> 00:32:58.699
companies, but what I see missing is that we don't have something that's a population as a whole

00:32:58.699 --> 00:33:03.979
type of data structure. Now, there's a lot of insurance companies that wouldn't like that

00:33:03.979 --> 00:33:15.339
because it could mean some competition, but I think we need more of that to level the playing

00:33:15.339 --> 00:33:24.459
field. Awesome. All right. You ready for a few more technical questions? Sure. Okay. There's an

00:33:24.459 --> 00:33:30.140
anonymous one here that I'm going to summarize a little bit. I'm sorry, anonymous asker. In risk

00:33:30.140 --> 00:33:37.099
evaluation, do you emphasize causal models or would you emphasize prediction models?

00:33:38.140 --> 00:33:43.579
Asked because identifying assumptions and wonder what you value more in risk evaluation.

00:33:46.060 --> 00:33:54.140
I learned a long time ago, a number is just a number and it's going to be wrong. Every model

00:33:54.859 --> 00:34:03.020
is wrong. What you have to understand is what's driving the model. If you don't understand

00:34:03.020 --> 00:34:08.620
what's driving the model, it could be the best model in the world, but it still is going to be

00:34:08.620 --> 00:34:16.540
wrong. I actually think you have to have a wide array of both in the process. There's no such

00:34:16.540 --> 00:34:23.419
thing, unless you can only have one model, there's no such thing. What I like about using a platform

00:34:23.419 --> 00:34:31.020
like Posit, it allows us to do multiple things all around the prediction process

00:34:31.979 --> 00:34:39.179
because it shouldn't be a one or the other. It should be what makes the sense for the problem

00:34:39.179 --> 00:34:48.780
at hand. Again, you always have to know the assumptions. In a good example, actuaries have

00:34:48.780 --> 00:34:54.379
very specific techniques in observing. Each one will give you a different answer on the exact

00:34:54.780 --> 00:35:02.620
same data. If you understand how those models work and what the assumptions were that go into

00:35:02.620 --> 00:35:08.699
them, you can actually level them to see if they're roughly the same. That's the important

00:35:08.699 --> 00:35:13.739
part. It's understanding what you're doing and what the question should be.

00:35:17.020 --> 00:35:20.379
Awesome. Thank you. Thank you, anonymous question asker, whoever you were.

00:35:21.340 --> 00:35:26.219
I have another question here from Chris. Chris, if you're available to unmute and ask it,

00:35:26.219 --> 00:35:28.219
that would be great. Otherwise, I can ask it for you.

00:35:34.540 --> 00:35:36.459
I can see Chris unmuted, but we can't hear you.

00:35:36.459 --> 00:35:37.899
There we go. Can't hear you yet.

00:35:42.060 --> 00:35:43.899
Maybe you ask and then we'll see.

00:35:44.699 --> 00:35:48.459
Chris, if you have any follow-ups and you're able to unmute, you just let me know. Okay.

00:35:49.260 --> 00:35:55.659
How are you adapting your actuarial models slash approaches to address the evolving risks

00:35:55.659 --> 00:36:01.260
introduced by recent advancements in AI and the resulting complexity, regulatory uncertainty,

00:36:01.260 --> 00:36:06.300
as well as ambiguity in liability slash accountability structures? I think this is a

00:36:06.300 --> 00:36:10.860
very complex question. I can repeat that if you need to. I'm going to highlight it for everybody

00:36:10.860 --> 00:36:19.820
in Slido. I appreciate the request. No, no. Actually, it's a very interesting question

00:36:19.820 --> 00:36:27.580
because it's evolving. The one thing you don't want to do is overreact because as folks are

00:36:27.580 --> 00:36:33.899
finding out now, one group of politicians took a path prior to the election and now that path's

00:36:33.899 --> 00:36:39.979
going in a different direction. The uncertainties have always been there. That's where you want to

00:36:39.979 --> 00:36:48.300
use types of scenario models, scenario planning type of activities from a risk standpoint.

00:36:48.939 --> 00:36:54.699
Scenario modeling is not just good for climate change. It's good for all kinds of things.

00:36:56.139 --> 00:37:01.500
What you want to do is test the various things. Again, it comes back kind of tied back to the

00:37:01.500 --> 00:37:05.179
prior answer. You want to know what the assumptions are and what you're doing.

00:37:05.820 --> 00:37:12.300
I've built a lot of models over the years and they are getting more sophisticated.

00:37:13.340 --> 00:37:20.379
The problem is that when you get more sophisticated, it doesn't take much to really

00:37:20.379 --> 00:37:26.459
make an issue within the model. I do believe in keeping models simple, as simple as possible.

00:37:26.780 --> 00:37:31.979
I would rather take 10 very simple models than one really good complex model.

00:37:33.260 --> 00:37:38.139
I think what you want to do is within all the models or a model you have,

00:37:39.020 --> 00:37:43.260
really outline the assumptions, stress the assumptions, vary those assumptions,

00:37:43.260 --> 00:37:49.020
and figure out where all those things are. The uncertainty is always going to be there.

00:37:49.419 --> 00:37:55.899
The question is, have you put a pathway for that potential uncertainty? It's okay to say we don't

00:37:55.899 --> 00:38:04.540
know that this is going to be the answer. When I wrote the pandemic paper, I got lucky. I got about

00:38:04.540 --> 00:38:12.540
80% of how the pandemic would work right and about 20% wrong. That's pretty good, but it was just a

00:38:13.500 --> 00:38:21.580
guess. You have to be comfortable in that and knowing that I took this down a path.

00:38:23.340 --> 00:38:24.620
That's all you really need to do.

00:38:27.500 --> 00:38:34.379
Thanks, Bill. We have one more question that has an asterisk next to it, so I will read it.

00:38:35.179 --> 00:38:39.340
It is along the lines of what we were talking about already. Lots of

00:38:40.300 --> 00:38:47.419
regulations in the insurance industry. How much more accurate could you get your models

00:38:47.979 --> 00:38:52.540
if there were not ethics or regulations? I think this is just a funny question.

00:38:52.540 --> 00:38:56.939
She says like ballpark. How much better could you do if you didn't have to worry about all that?

00:38:59.340 --> 00:39:04.219
Well, if I didn't have to worry about ethics and regulations, we could get some very sophisticated,

00:39:05.100 --> 00:39:08.459
highly accurate models where no one would buy the insurance.

00:39:11.739 --> 00:39:19.179
Insurance is a pooling mechanism. That's how it started out. When people started to

00:39:19.179 --> 00:39:23.580
try to compete, that's where a lot of this stuff really started to come into,

00:39:23.580 --> 00:39:32.459
the segmentation. You can only segment so far because some people are just bad risks

00:39:33.419 --> 00:39:39.020
and the rest of us have to make up for them. Again, insurance is actually a community product.

00:39:40.699 --> 00:39:47.979
We put our money into a pool just in case something bad happens. To some people,

00:39:47.979 --> 00:39:55.260
something bad happens all the time. The question is, how specific do you want to get?

00:39:56.219 --> 00:40:04.219
I mean, do you want people to have insurance? If you want people to have insurance,

00:40:04.780 --> 00:40:14.860
you have to lose some of that specificity. Again, it comes down to what's your goal?

00:40:14.860 --> 00:40:20.699
I believe in the mechanism of insurance. Do I want to pay more than I have to? No,

00:40:21.260 --> 00:40:29.419
but I'm going to have to so everybody can get it. What's your passion for wanting to help other

00:40:29.419 --> 00:40:39.659
people? Thank you. Catherine Girton in the chat had a really great comment. Catherine,

00:40:39.659 --> 00:40:44.780
I was hoping you could hop in. Catherine is a community member here. She's also a former

00:40:44.780 --> 00:40:48.780
featured leader. If you're available to unmute and chime in here, I'd love that.

00:40:49.340 --> 00:40:57.179
Yeah. My comment in the chat was just, I find that models that impact actual people's health

00:40:57.179 --> 00:41:03.020
outcomes or safety outcomes or cost outcomes, speaking as a data scientist embedded in an

00:41:03.020 --> 00:41:09.979
actuarial department, need to be explainable before anything else. Those simple models that

00:41:09.979 --> 00:41:18.139
you know exactly how the model got there become so much more important than we threw it into a

00:41:18.139 --> 00:41:25.020
black box model. We were 97% accurate, and we can't tell you why. If you're going to deny someone

00:41:25.020 --> 00:41:32.939
coverage, you need to be able to justify that. I was curious as to how you find that paradigm

00:41:33.979 --> 00:41:41.340
and that balance within some of the work that you do as an actuary or as an insurance provider.

00:41:42.060 --> 00:41:46.060
What does it look like for you to strike that balance between explainability and accuracy?

00:41:48.139 --> 00:41:58.379
Without transparency, there is no model. You cannot charge someone something. You cannot

00:41:59.260 --> 00:42:08.939
deny someone something unless there's full transparency. There is absolutely no

00:42:10.300 --> 00:42:15.899
black box at all. I'm going to say our executive management is so on board with that.

00:42:16.699 --> 00:42:22.540
If we cannot explain it to a third grader, we can't do it.

00:42:24.939 --> 00:42:30.620
Thanks, Bill. I will agree as someone who has worked in so many industries that touch

00:42:30.620 --> 00:42:35.260
things that people care about, if you are messing with people's health, their money, or their food,

00:42:36.300 --> 00:42:39.739
you better be ready to explain every ounce of what you're doing.

00:42:40.699 --> 00:42:47.500
All right. I have so many questions in Slido. Somehow, we are 12 minutes to the top of the hour.

00:42:47.500 --> 00:42:51.739
Let's see how many questions I can throw at Bill and have him answer in 12 minutes,

00:42:51.739 --> 00:42:57.340
or maybe more like 10 minutes. Okay. Morgana, I see you've got a question that has been waiting

00:42:57.340 --> 00:43:01.179
around here. If you have the ability to unmute and ask, I would love that if you're still with us.

00:43:02.139 --> 00:43:08.780
Yes, I am. My question was about causal analysis. I'm trying to learn more about it

00:43:09.419 --> 00:43:15.820
and reading that book of why, which is really good. My observation was that it sounds like

00:43:15.820 --> 00:43:22.219
actuaries think a lot in terms of counterfactuals and what if this happened type scenarios very

00:43:22.219 --> 00:43:28.540
often. I'm wondering, in your experience, does the insurance field tend to think in terms of

00:43:28.540 --> 00:43:33.820
cause and effect, or is it more in terms of the probability that something might occur?

00:43:34.699 --> 00:43:42.139
We combine the two. It's an iterative process, especially if the risk is new

00:43:42.699 --> 00:43:47.179
and there's no information. That's when you really have to start thinking

00:43:47.899 --> 00:43:53.820
and putting things together. Until you start collecting that information, it really is,

00:43:55.100 --> 00:44:01.020
if this, then this could happen. Sometimes, you have to assign the weights to them to get down

00:44:01.419 --> 00:44:09.899
the path. For certain things, let's say the fires in Los Angeles, as an example,

00:44:11.260 --> 00:44:15.340
there's enough modeling and enough data out there to give you some fairly accurate

00:44:16.060 --> 00:44:22.300
ideas of what's going to go on and what could happen pretty quickly. It's really then,

00:44:23.100 --> 00:44:27.659
what's the starter point? Because once the fire started and they saw the spread,

00:44:27.739 --> 00:44:35.899
everybody knew what was going to happen with the information. It's an evolving thing. The earlier

00:44:35.899 --> 00:44:46.780
the risk is in its life, the more you're going to look at what ifs and what could be. As the

00:44:47.419 --> 00:44:53.100
product line matures, it becomes less about causality because you've already got that down

00:44:53.659 --> 00:44:59.739
for the most part. That's when you get into the more probabilistic type of activity.

00:45:00.780 --> 00:45:08.139
It's a spectrum. As things change, I mean, I've been doing a lot of work on climate

00:45:09.179 --> 00:45:16.780
understanding and just watching what's happened in those models as things have transposed. It's

00:45:16.780 --> 00:45:24.780
a good example. They've gone from all causal with a whole bunch of guesses to now that they've

00:45:24.780 --> 00:45:29.100
captured data and they've figured out how to do certain calculations, they can make it more

00:45:29.100 --> 00:45:37.500
probabilistic. Again, it's a maturity thing more than anything else. That makes a lot of sense.

00:45:37.500 --> 00:45:42.540
Thanks for going to that. Thanks, Mark. That's a nice question. Thank you. Yeah, that's a great

00:45:42.540 --> 00:45:49.899
question. I see a couple of questions about POSIT tools. I saw that Rachel had asked about

00:45:49.899 --> 00:45:54.620
use cases. I think this is a good question to get context. Rachel, would you like to ask that?

00:45:55.979 --> 00:46:00.379
Yeah, I see somebody asked the question anonymously too, which is kind of in line.

00:46:00.379 --> 00:46:06.620
It said, what is the best story you have told with data using POSIT tools? Then I kind of

00:46:06.620 --> 00:46:11.419
wanted to ask a selfish question because I'm trying to start writing a few more insurance

00:46:11.500 --> 00:46:17.260
spotlights and because I've never worked in the insurance industry, it's really helpful for me

00:46:17.260 --> 00:46:24.699
when I have a specific use case or project to kind of have in the back of my mind. I was just

00:46:24.699 --> 00:46:31.419
wondering if you could tell us about a specific use case. I'd rather have my data science team

00:46:31.419 --> 00:46:40.540
do that because they're much smarter and better at it than I am. For us, I'm going to... I still

00:46:40.540 --> 00:46:53.500
call it our studio. Sorry. They have gotten a lot of traction using those kinds of tools for what I

00:46:53.500 --> 00:47:01.020
call the operational side of the world. We have a premium audit department. For those who don't

00:47:01.020 --> 00:47:07.179
understand, for large accounts, they give us premium upfront, but depending on how many people

00:47:07.179 --> 00:47:14.860
they have or don't have employed, their premium can change either up or down. At times, you could

00:47:14.860 --> 00:47:24.620
talk hundreds of thousands of dollars swinging any direction. We are obliged by law to make sure

00:47:24.620 --> 00:47:33.899
that they either pay or we give back the amount that we should. For us though, because we have

00:47:33.899 --> 00:47:43.020
so many clients, one of my team's projects was to go out and to basically figure out who should

00:47:43.020 --> 00:47:48.699
they talk to first. Who has a significant variance from year to year and who doesn't.

00:47:49.340 --> 00:47:55.500
It's that type of use case in improving operational efficiency because it allows us to

00:47:55.500 --> 00:48:02.459
get to those clients who we either owe money to or they owe money to us. It helps us

00:48:02.459 --> 00:48:07.419
figure out where we should be as an organization. That operational use case is

00:48:08.379 --> 00:48:13.419
really well suited if you structured it right for closet type of tools.

00:48:15.500 --> 00:48:23.179
Thank you, Bill. All righty. We have six minutes left. How many more questions can we get in here?

00:48:23.179 --> 00:48:27.179
I have an anonymous question. That's just what's your view on artificial intelligence within the

00:48:27.179 --> 00:48:34.379
actuarial world? I'm old school. I still call it machine learning. There's no such thing as

00:48:34.379 --> 00:48:40.540
artificial intelligence. I think it's very useful. Actually, I just wrote an internal paper.

00:48:41.419 --> 00:48:47.179
I cannot provide it outside because it is for us on how it should be used with an actuarial

00:48:47.500 --> 00:48:52.860
world in certain respects. The tools are going to make...

00:48:54.620 --> 00:49:01.500
This is a double-edged sword. The tools are great. I loathe them to death because they make me

00:49:02.219 --> 00:49:08.459
more efficient because I can do certain things. What I worry about with the tools

00:49:09.419 --> 00:49:18.699
is the lack of prior knowledge. I've been doing this 40 years. I've been able to see things

00:49:18.699 --> 00:49:23.820
and understand why they work. I've actually made the comment to a colleague,

00:49:23.820 --> 00:49:30.780
I started with punch cards. Then I went to a dumb terminal. Then I went to the first personal

00:49:30.780 --> 00:49:36.379
computer. Then I went to network computers. As all that technology has done, what I still have

00:49:37.260 --> 00:49:43.020
that I don't see a lot of people today is understanding the underlying concepts.

00:49:45.179 --> 00:49:50.939
You can take a tool and throw a lot of models at it, but you really do need that underlying

00:49:50.939 --> 00:49:58.459
concept stuff first. I think AI is going to really speed up and make people better

00:49:59.419 --> 00:50:03.899
as long as they have the underlying knowledge they need with the tool.

00:50:06.139 --> 00:50:08.699
My biggest concern is that we're not teaching people enough

00:50:10.139 --> 00:50:12.939
about some of the harder things that they haven't done yet.

00:50:15.820 --> 00:50:20.699
Awesome. Thank you. I see a question in Slido that might be really easy for us to

00:50:21.899 --> 00:50:25.500
answer, which is, is there a way for us to read the paper that you're talking about,

00:50:25.500 --> 00:50:28.060
the pandemic paper? The pandemic? No.

00:50:30.060 --> 00:50:36.620
I wish, but no. We'll go ahead and move on to that one.

00:50:43.100 --> 00:50:48.459
No, we can't do that. We only have a few minutes left. Let's try one more question.

00:50:49.419 --> 00:50:58.860
I think, Arthur, I really like your question to send us out. If you're available to ask that

00:50:59.500 --> 00:51:02.060
and unmute, I would love that. Otherwise, I can ask it for you.

00:51:04.540 --> 00:51:07.739
Sorry, I'm a little delayed in going to the unmute button. There you go, Arthur.

00:51:07.739 --> 00:51:15.659
That's okay. Thanks. I was like, I'm trying to unmute. My question was, given your comments

00:51:15.659 --> 00:51:20.219
about how things are no longer, quote, unquote, once in a lifetime and will be speeding up,

00:51:21.260 --> 00:51:25.580
what do you see as the role of insurance, broadly speaking, going into the future? It seems like

00:51:25.580 --> 00:51:31.419
things are going to get harder and harder to pull in a way that works out in the math.

00:51:33.020 --> 00:51:39.820
Actually, it is. I sit on what's called a General Research Council for the Society of Actuaries.

00:51:39.820 --> 00:51:46.780
We started talking about this because certain risks, I don't think, fit into the insurance

00:51:46.780 --> 00:51:54.459
mechanism anymore. We need, as a group of really smart people, to figure out how to get them taken

00:51:54.459 --> 00:52:01.899
care of because they still need to be taken care of. You don't want to leave anyone in a bad state.

00:52:02.699 --> 00:52:08.060
The question becomes, who are the right people in the room and what are the things that need to be

00:52:08.060 --> 00:52:14.540
done? Because you see it happening in Florida. You're going to see it really happening in

00:52:14.540 --> 00:52:22.939
California. The state is going to have to start taking a bigger burden, which means everyone in

00:52:22.939 --> 00:52:26.860
that state is going to be taking a bigger burden because the insurance mechanism

00:52:27.820 --> 00:52:35.659
wasn't built for mass casualty events. If you look at all the mechanics behind it,

00:52:35.659 --> 00:52:44.139
it really is supposed to be the low probability, higher severity type of thing. Instead of an

00:52:44.139 --> 00:52:50.860
entire community burning down, it's a house in that community. That's how it was originally

00:52:50.860 --> 00:52:59.739
built. It's transformed over a generation. We, as a group, need to do something.

00:53:00.620 --> 00:53:05.340
You're going to need to involve regulators. You're going to need to involve the insurance

00:53:05.340 --> 00:53:11.100
industry, but you're going to need to involve the communities too, to see how best, because

00:53:11.100 --> 00:53:20.219
every community has something different. You are going to have to sometimes reach outside of

00:53:21.179 --> 00:53:29.020
our geopolitical sphere to get a solution. It's a complicated thing. We are trying to

00:53:29.899 --> 00:53:35.100
think about it now, but some things are going to be uninsurable.

00:53:36.780 --> 00:53:41.979
Awesome. Thank you, Bill. Thank you so much for all of your insights and sharing everything with

00:53:41.979 --> 00:53:50.699
us today. I will wrap it up there because we have a minute left. I want to say thank you to Bill and

00:53:50.699 --> 00:53:56.860
to everybody for showing up. I would really like to let you know who's coming up next week as well.

00:53:56.860 --> 00:54:01.739
We have Victoria Prince, Senior Manager of Statistics at Takeda Pharmaceuticals.

00:54:02.540 --> 00:54:07.580
I'm going to put in the chat here for you a link to her page on the Data Science Hangout website,

00:54:07.580 --> 00:54:12.939
so you can go check her out. Find her on LinkedIn. Thank you so much, everybody,

00:54:12.939 --> 00:54:18.780
for making this a wonderful discussion. We will see you next week. Everyone have a wonderful day.

